{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5d1cde87-6738-467c-9ac0-330b3e6540df","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone isn't enough — you need platform-specific handling for both iOS and Android. Here's what's likely missing:\n\n**1. iOS — disable safe-area insets on the page:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**2. Android — opt into edge-to-edge rendering** in `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    \n    if (Window != null)\n    {\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n(Add `using AndroidX.Core.View;`)\n\n**3. Hide the navigation bar** if you're inside a `Shell` or `NavigationPage`:\n\n```xml\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n<!-- or -->\nNavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n```\n\n**4. Make sure your Image fills the layout:**\n\n```xml\n<Grid>\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\nThe most common culprit is #2 — Android doesn't draw behind system bars by default, so even with safe-area settings, the content stops at the status/nav bar boundaries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"467a8d2d-77c8-4e04-bfa3-5f8e1d8dc72a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still have padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to go truly edge-to-edge, you need to:\n\n1. Set `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the layout/view level, not just the page level\n2. On Android, you may need to handle the edge-to-edge display mode\n\n\n3. The approach differs between iOS and Android—`SafeAreaEdges` is iOS-specific, while Android requires different handling depending on the version, and recent MAUI updates have improved edge-to-edge support for Android 15 and later.\n\nThe real issue is likely that on iOS, the user needs `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage plus `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the layout containing the Image, while on Android they need to ensure the window is configured to extend behind system bars. I'm realizing `SafeAreaEdges` might not be the actual MAUI property—the correct one is likely `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` for iOS. On Android, they'll need to configure edge-to-edge mode in the platform-specific code, possibly in `MainActivity.cs`, and I should also consider whether a NavigationBar or Shell is adding unwanted padding. For navigation elements, I should mention that hiding the navigation bar with `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` or `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` might be necessary since those components consume space. I'm also recalling that .NET 9 introduced the `Activity.EdgeToEdge` API for Android, which .NET 10 likely builds on, so I should focus my answer on the platform-specific approaches and clarify that `SafeAreaEdges` might not be the right property to rely on here.","outputTokens":1695,"requestId":"7FDA:133174:45B267E:4C3629D:69F15960"},"id":"dcf97d2e-34eb-44c3-885b-1ddf48f5b552","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:06:09.854Z","parentId":"6c4c9685-2ea2-45fb-a6cc-370e4f67a7f1"}
